● This is the smoking gun. Confirmed diagnosis:

  - Cache: skbuff_small_head (not skbuff_head_cache — that was a merged alias;
  slab_nomerge revealed the actual cache).
  - Type: classic write-after-free. Object at 0xffff8b15dc6886c0 was freed
  (poison 0x6b filled the whole body) — except offset 0–7 was overwritten with
  68 0d 23 a9 fa 08 8d 1a (a kernel pointer-shaped value: 0x1a8d08fa a9230d68).
  Some path freed the SKB head and then wrote a pointer back into byte 0.
  - Detection path is just the next consumer (__tcp_send_ack from tailscale's
  TUN write); producer is invisible by design — slub_debug=FZP only validates at
   next allocation, not at the bad write.
  - Crash time: 354 s after boot. No s2idle cycle this run (user was actively at
   the keyboard). That falsifies the s2idle-only theory — corruption happens
  during plain normal operation.

  The drivers in the consumer stack and recently loaded ones that touch SKBs
  are: mt7925e (WiFi 7), tun (legit, kernel core), amdxdna, amd_isp4, amd_pmf.
  WiFi drivers handle SKB lifecycle constantly and mt7925e on Strix Halo is the
